00:02:50.902 --> 00:02:52.610
But I write a little
bit more in the book

00:02:52.610 --> 00:02:55.350
about guys left behind, because
it's the kind of book it is.

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:58.550
I try to write about the
things you're not necessarily

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:00.770
reading about everyday.

00:03:00.770 --> 00:03:05.140
And I'll give you kind
of an overview of some

00:03:05.140 --> 00:03:09.520
of the reasons behind the
development of microtrends

00:03:09.520 --> 00:03:11.140
10 years later.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:14.490
First, when we go back
to economic development,

00:03:14.490 --> 00:03:18.070
and let's go back to the
beginning of the 20th century

00:03:18.070 --> 00:03:22.220
when Henry Ford said, "you can
have any color of car you want,

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:26.170
as long as it's black," and
what the Ford economy was about

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:30.400
was about standardization
of the manufacturer of goods

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:33.910
so that everybody could
have goods like a car.

00:03:33.910 --> 00:03:37.000
And they envisioned that the
way the world would be clothed,

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:41.260
housed, fed, and
have products would

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:43.420
be through this level
of standardization.

00:03:43.420 --> 00:03:44.770
That was the idea.

00:03:44.770 --> 00:03:47.080
But that's not what turned out.

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:51.730
People, in fact, love
choice, love to be different.

00:03:51.730 --> 00:03:56.650
And not so long ago, I
think we evolved to what

00:03:56.650 --> 00:03:58.910
I call the Starbucks economy.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:02.290
Take a basic
commodity, like coffee,

00:04:02.290 --> 00:04:06.700
any color you want as long as
it's black, and instead now,

00:04:06.700 --> 00:04:10.960
create 155 different varieties
of a simple commodity,

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:13.000
and give people a
world of choice.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:18.190
Now, in that case really,
the barista does the work.

00:04:18.190 --> 00:04:20.124
Starbucks does the work for you.

00:04:20.124 --> 00:04:23.860
In most tech platforms, if you
think of the original iPod,

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:25.540
the iPod was any color
you want, as long

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:28.240
as it's white for a long time.

00:04:28.240 --> 00:04:31.270
And you did the work
making the soundtrack.

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:34.454
Today there's a third
choice, AI, like a Pandora

00:04:34.454 --> 00:04:35.620
that actually does the work.

00:04:35.620 --> 00:04:37.360
But the goal is the same.

00:04:37.360 --> 00:04:39.880
To basically produce
customized products

00:04:39.880 --> 00:04:41.540
that drive the marketplace.

00:04:41.540 --> 00:04:47.210
Today, as I say, we are actually
advanced to the Uber economy.

00:04:47.210 --> 00:04:49.550
And what do I mean by that?

00:04:49.550 --> 00:04:54.180
Uber has to in an instant
provide you with a service

00:04:54.180 --> 00:04:56.570
slash its product
that can take you

00:04:56.570 --> 00:04:59.000
from any point to any point.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.870
It is a totally customized,
individualized product.

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:07.220
And so the name of the game
has gone, in microtrends,

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:12.190
from these clusters
down to the individual.

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:15.310
Hold that thought.

00:05:15.310 --> 00:05:19.240
Now we have what I'd say is
one of the counter intuitive

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:21.780
properties of more choice.

00:05:21.780 --> 00:05:24.610
I like to illustrate
it with a restaurant.

00:05:24.610 --> 00:05:27.520
So suppose we had
a restaurant that

00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:31.420
just served chicken or fish.

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:33.880
Who really cares that
much about the choices?

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:37.160
Chicken or fish every day.

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:41.260
Now, let's add steak and sushi.

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.970
Well, now we get
some real passion.

00:05:43.970 --> 00:05:47.100
The steak eaters love
Kansas City strips.

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:48.930
Sushi eaters love toro.

00:05:48.930 --> 00:05:50.850
They really burrow
into their choices.

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:53.910
And so every day
they don't actually

00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:56.130
get chicken or fish anymore.

00:05:56.130 --> 00:05:58.359
They get their own choice
over and over again,

00:05:58.359 --> 00:06:00.150
because they love it
so much, because we've

00:06:00.150 --> 00:06:02.370
done such an incredible job.

00:06:02.370 --> 00:06:05.100
And then, just to
boot, the sushi people

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:08.539
say, wow, those meat
eaters, they're really-- ah,

00:06:08.539 --> 00:06:09.330
can you believe it?

00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:11.170
That just kills you.

00:06:11.170 --> 00:06:12.640
And the meat eaters
start to say,

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:16.120
can you believe over there
they're eating raw fish?

00:06:16.120 --> 00:06:19.230
That'll just give you
E. coli in a minute.

00:06:19.230 --> 00:06:21.270
So they begin not only
to love their choice,

00:06:21.270 --> 00:06:23.700
but they begin to
get antagonistic

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:25.530
towards the other choices.

00:06:25.530 --> 00:06:26.190
All right.

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:29.460
Now think Fox News and MSNBC.

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:30.200
OK.

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:34.220
Understand that by giving
people more choice,

00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:36.230
they stop making choices.

00:06:36.230 --> 00:06:38.300
They burrow into their choices.

00:06:38.300 --> 00:06:41.730
And we get exactly the opposite
result of what we intended,

00:06:41.730 --> 00:06:44.180
which was to have a world
of freedom and choice,

00:06:44.180 --> 00:06:45.260
people experimenting.

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:47.510
And then you fast
forward 10 years later

00:06:47.510 --> 00:06:48.950
when they go into Starbucks.

00:06:48.950 --> 00:06:51.320
What do people ask for?

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:53.140
The regular.

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:54.610
They've stopped making choices.

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:56.450
And so this is a problem.

00:06:56.450 --> 00:07:00.955
It's a problem of us being
so good at providing choices.

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:06.610
Now, another major
thought in the book.

00:07:06.610 --> 00:07:08.960
For every trend there
is a counter trend.

00:07:08.960 --> 00:07:12.910
I call it the my
Newtonian law of trends.

00:07:12.910 --> 00:07:15.220
Now, the difference
between me and Newton

00:07:15.220 --> 00:07:16.870
is that in Newton
every trend had

00:07:16.870 --> 00:07:19.459
to have an opposite
and equal reaction.

00:07:19.459 --> 00:07:21.250
These do not have to
be opposite and equal.

00:07:21.250 --> 00:07:24.430
At any time the trend
or the counter-trend

00:07:24.430 --> 00:07:26.800
can be bigger or smaller.

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:30.340
The trend for sushi can
have a trend for steak.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:33.160
The trend towards
technology on the train

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:35.380
can have the quiet car.

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:36.880
It doesn't have to
be the same size.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:39.450
But often times there
is a battle or shifting.

00:07:39.450 --> 00:07:42.700
And, in fact, the cover of
the book, you look at it,

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:44.920
it's a Newton's cradle in
an impossible position.

00:07:44.920 --> 00:07:48.850
Because in the Newtonian
theory of trends here,

00:07:48.850 --> 00:07:52.280
these trends can ebb and flow.

00:07:52.280 --> 00:07:57.780
So what are some major trends
and counter trends today?

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:01.080
Everybody knows we're in
the age of information.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.130
At the very same
time, of course,

00:08:03.130 --> 00:08:05.550
we are in the age
of misinformation.

00:08:05.550 --> 00:08:07.470
Never before has there
been so much discussion

00:08:07.470 --> 00:08:09.870
about false information.

00:08:09.870 --> 00:08:10.770
Millennials?

00:08:10.770 --> 00:08:11.490
Wow.

00:08:11.490 --> 00:08:14.280
Can't stop talking about
how important they are.

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:16.650
There are now more
nonagenarians than ever,

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:18.410
as we'll come back to.

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:19.230
Smartphones?

00:08:19.230 --> 00:08:19.800
Sure.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:21.480
Everybody has some.

00:08:21.480 --> 00:08:23.400
They just had an
uptick last year

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:27.060
in flip phone manufacturing
to 2 million a year.

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.430
Every trend there's
a counter trend.

00:08:29.430 --> 00:08:33.210
Silicon Valley versus the old
economy, and the old economy

00:08:33.210 --> 00:08:33.870
voters.

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:35.520
I think that's
probably the biggest

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:38.580
conflict of the
last couple of years

00:08:38.580 --> 00:08:42.299
is those Silicon
Valley voters, voters

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:45.630
on the coast who did very well
with the rise of technology,

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:48.960
were pitted in a battle against
the old economy voters who

00:08:48.960 --> 00:08:52.710
were losing more and more
as manufacturing jobs shrunk

00:08:52.710 --> 00:08:55.860
from 20 million when I left,
working with President Clinton,

00:08:55.860 --> 00:08:58.170
to about 11 million.

00:08:58.170 --> 00:09:00.260
And two others.

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:03.240
Egghead policies versus
commonsense policies.

00:09:03.240 --> 00:09:07.800
Think things like climate change
versus, hey, Iran's our enemy.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:08.490
Bop them.

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:09.390
You know what I mean?

00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:13.230
A much more simpler
view of policy.

00:09:13.230 --> 00:09:14.650
And educated?

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:17.110
We have never been
more educated.

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:19.740
And I have a chapter on what I
call the impression of elites.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.110
Never before have so
many educated people

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:24.630
made so many conclusions
that they believe in

00:09:24.630 --> 00:09:26.110
on so little evidence.

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:29.320
In fact, it turns out the
more educated you are,

00:09:29.320 --> 00:09:30.840
the more spinnable you are.

00:09:30.840 --> 00:09:32.850
And I happened to
run for a while

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:36.030
a large company called Burson
Marsteller that was dedicated

00:09:36.030 --> 00:09:37.920
to that very proposition.

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:41.650
So those are some of the flows
and ebbs and counter-forces.

00:09:41.650 --> 00:09:43.770
And how do you apply
this to the election?

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:45.760
What are some trends
and counter trends?

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:48.540
Well, as I said to you
before, old economy voters

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:50.700
felt neglected.

00:09:50.700 --> 00:09:55.020
If you look at it, the
60 million ex voters

00:09:55.020 --> 00:09:58.140
for Donald Trump
lived in communities

00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:00.110
that got a third of the GDP.

00:10:00.110 --> 00:10:03.180
And the 60 odd million
voters for Hillary Clinton

00:10:03.180 --> 00:10:06.270
lived in communities
that got 2/3 of the GDP.

00:10:06.270 --> 00:10:10.260
Well, the voters with 1/3
said, where's my half?

00:10:10.260 --> 00:10:11.550
OK.

00:10:11.550 --> 00:10:15.470
And they stood up and exercised
their democratic power.

00:10:15.470 --> 00:10:19.500
And they had
economic grievances.

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:24.120
And they also, as primarily more
older, more rural based voters,

00:10:24.120 --> 00:10:28.210
had a huge cultural gap
between millennial voters,

00:10:28.210 --> 00:10:31.800
particularly when it came
to family and religion.

00:10:31.800 --> 00:10:34.650
Society, as I said to you,
is divided more and more

00:10:34.650 --> 00:10:38.865
into niches that then see
each other less and less.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:45.860
And, in fact, we have about the
same number of conservatives

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:47.540
and about the same
number of liberals.

00:10:47.540 --> 00:10:52.970
But we have more very liberals,
more very conservative voters.

00:10:52.970 --> 00:10:55.160
And those impressionable elites?

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:59.420
When they believe something,
boy, they all believe it.

00:10:59.420 --> 00:11:02.510
So "The New York Times"
said that it was 93 to 7,

00:11:02.510 --> 00:11:03.900
Hillary was going to win.

00:11:03.900 --> 00:11:05.420
They were in their
own environment.

00:11:05.420 --> 00:11:06.800
The impressionable elites.

00:11:06.800 --> 00:11:08.540
The kind of election analysis.

00:11:08.540 --> 00:11:11.000
Look, how could billions
and billions of dollars

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.220
have been spent on this
election problem, who's

00:11:13.220 --> 00:11:16.820
going to win by how much in
the electoral college, and not

00:11:16.820 --> 00:11:21.490
a single person in the universe
posted an accurate memo?

00:11:21.490 --> 00:11:24.330
The most accurate person is
actually Kellyanne Conway,

00:11:24.330 --> 00:11:28.310
who goes on TV, almost exactly
predicts the electoral college,

00:11:28.310 --> 00:11:32.030
and is laughed at during
the entire interview.

00:11:32.030 --> 00:11:35.820
So a couple of other
things floating around.

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:38.250
Changes in lifestyle.

00:11:38.250 --> 00:11:41.010
Very powerfully,
people typically

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:44.490
had a high school sweetheart,
got married pretty quickly,

00:11:44.490 --> 00:11:45.960
didn't go to college.

00:11:45.960 --> 00:11:47.880
Now, people go to college.

00:11:47.880 --> 00:11:50.520
Men and women are
in the workforce.

00:11:50.520 --> 00:11:52.990
Child rearing and marriage
have been pushed back.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.740
And there's a good 10 or 15
years that a lot of people

00:11:55.740 --> 00:11:57.570
have on their own.

00:11:57.570 --> 00:12:01.740
And that is a whole new space
in life that just didn't exist.

00:12:01.740 --> 00:12:03.750
And I'll come back to that.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:05.940
Seniors, on the other
hand, have the same thing

00:12:05.940 --> 00:12:10.710
in this kind of accordioning of
life where they have more years

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:11.972
now than they ever had.

00:12:11.972 --> 00:12:13.680
Have a pretty good
chance, if you make it

00:12:13.680 --> 00:12:16.380
to 65, to make it to 80 or 90.

00:12:16.380 --> 00:12:17.430
They're living longer.

00:12:17.430 --> 00:12:19.030
They have more money
than ever before.

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:20.821
They're doing more
dating than ever before.

00:12:20.821 --> 00:12:23.130
They're having more fun.

00:12:23.130 --> 00:12:26.190
And, of course, we've had a huge
migration from the rural areas

00:12:26.190 --> 00:12:27.720
to the cities.

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:31.560
And as you guys know,
data is the new gold.

00:12:31.560 --> 00:12:33.660
AI bots are coming.

00:12:33.660 --> 00:12:35.760
Big data is here.

00:12:35.760 --> 00:12:39.330
And I only have some
really grainy picture

00:12:39.330 --> 00:12:40.650
of my grandparents.

00:12:40.650 --> 00:12:44.370
But today the data on you could
start as early as the womb.

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:46.560
And the incredible
data file that you

00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:49.140
have for your entire
life is unlike anything

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:51.490
the world has ever had before.

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:53.565
So I take those as
backdrops to kind of think

00:12:53.565 --> 00:12:57.390
in your head of what actually
some of the bigger trends are.

00:12:57.390 --> 00:13:00.210
And now let's get really small.

