Chicken became actually
the protein of compromise.

00:24:42.384 --> 00:24:44.050
And if you take a
look at what happened,

00:24:44.050 --> 00:24:46.480
you take a little
trend, like the change

00:24:46.480 --> 00:24:49.720
in the recommendation for
protein versus carbohydrates,

00:24:49.720 --> 00:24:55.120
chicken consumption went from
20 pounds a year to 90 pounds.

00:24:55.120 --> 00:24:57.040
And that's an incredible
growth of what

00:24:57.040 --> 00:24:59.170
you think of as a simple
commodity industry.

00:24:59.170 --> 00:25:02.530
I immediately bought
more chicken stock

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:05.530
after doing the
research on the chapter.

00:25:05.530 --> 00:25:06.760
Old economy voters.

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:12.760
As I said before,
really the half

00:25:12.760 --> 00:25:16.300
of the country that lived
in a third of the GDP

00:25:16.300 --> 00:25:21.190
got really angry about the
other half of the country

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:24.130
that lives in those places
with 2/3 of the GDP.

00:25:24.130 --> 00:25:26.590
And they said, where's my half?

00:25:26.590 --> 00:25:28.750
Because their half
has disappeared.

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:32.320
And this created social
problems under the radar screen

00:25:32.320 --> 00:25:34.420
that we really didn't see.

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:37.300
And I thought actually during
the Clinton administration

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:40.690
that I worked with, we had
stabilized manufacturing jobs.

00:25:40.690 --> 00:25:42.640
I was really
surprised to find how

00:25:42.640 --> 00:25:46.360
they had fallen in half under
the last two presidencies,

00:25:46.360 --> 00:25:48.070
without any attention.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:52.180
This is a great example of how
what is a microtrend turns out

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:54.700
to be so powerful
a number of years

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:58.690
later, particularly when
it's neglected early on.

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:00.880
Another problem in
the system is what

00:26:00.880 --> 00:26:03.310
I call couch potato voters.

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:07.360
So with couch potato
voters, 90 million Americans

00:26:07.360 --> 00:26:10.240
are eligible to
vote, but don't vote.

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:11.710
It's too many.

00:26:11.710 --> 00:26:14.350
Why is it too many?

00:26:14.350 --> 00:26:18.340
It's too many because it
now encourages campaigns

00:26:18.340 --> 00:26:25.750
to use really tough
divisive messages

00:26:25.750 --> 00:26:29.380
to try to get a slice of
their potato to turn out more

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:31.420
than somebody else's slice.

00:26:31.420 --> 00:26:35.410
And when I ran campaigns that
went for swing voters, than

00:26:35.410 --> 00:26:38.650
typically I would be trying
to pitch to the other side.

00:26:38.650 --> 00:26:41.136
And after I won, the
country would be unified,

00:26:41.136 --> 00:26:43.510
because I spent two years
trying to get people who didn't

00:26:43.510 --> 00:26:45.160
agree with me to agree with me.

00:26:45.160 --> 00:26:49.660
If I spend two years just trying
to get a slice off the couch,

00:26:49.660 --> 00:26:52.191
I am probably, in
fact, dividing society.

00:26:52.191 --> 00:26:54.190
And then we wind up with
a more divided society.

00:26:54.190 --> 00:26:57.910
If we could have registration
at birth, for example.

00:26:57.910 --> 00:27:00.325
I suggest voting
at ATM machines.

00:27:00.325 --> 00:27:02.800
It's a secure
network, distributed

00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:04.670
throughout the country.

00:27:04.670 --> 00:27:06.730
I think we could
do a lot of things.

00:27:06.730 --> 00:27:08.960
And the couch, by the
way, will surprise you.

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:12.395
It's mostly downscale,
uneducated white voters

00:27:12.395 --> 00:27:13.270
who are on the couch.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:17.620
But we've got to
solve that problem.

00:27:17.620 --> 00:27:21.460
It will actually make for
much more unification.

00:27:21.460 --> 00:27:25.540
Then most of you here
won't really recall Hazel.

00:27:25.540 --> 00:27:29.110
But she was the housekeeper
that really ran everything,

00:27:29.110 --> 00:27:31.330
the archetype of that.

00:27:31.330 --> 00:27:36.190
And what I kind of make out
is that today people typically

00:27:36.190 --> 00:27:37.540
don't have one housekeeper.

00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:40.510
But what they have is
10 different people

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:43.840
let into their lives.

00:27:43.840 --> 00:27:47.830
We could start with their yoga
instructor, their trainer,

00:27:47.830 --> 00:27:53.050
their dog walker, the
manicurist, the hairdresser

00:27:53.050 --> 00:27:54.430
or barber.

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:59.200
And so really now actually they
have a flood of service people

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:02.770
who really do know intimate
details of your life.

00:28:02.770 --> 00:28:06.010
And, in fact, we've gone
from a 40% service economy

00:28:06.010 --> 00:28:08.470
to a 56% service economy.

00:28:08.470 --> 00:28:10.420
And when people get
more money today,

00:28:10.420 --> 00:28:13.190
they don't necessarily
say I want another car.

00:28:13.190 --> 00:28:15.850
In fact, they don't have a
driver's license, many of them.

00:28:15.850 --> 00:28:18.250
So what they really say
is, I want another service.

00:28:18.250 --> 00:28:19.660
I want another massage.

00:28:19.660 --> 00:28:23.680
I want something that really
pleases me personally.

00:28:23.680 --> 00:28:26.230
And that is a tremendous
trend, both in terms

00:28:26.230 --> 00:28:30.040
of creating an enormous
personal service industry,

00:28:30.040 --> 00:28:33.190
and in, I think, creating jobs.

00:28:33.190 --> 00:28:35.860
So having given you a
flavor of microtrends,

00:28:35.860 --> 00:28:41.440
I hope you will read the
other 37 and make up your own.

00:28:41.440 --> 00:28:46.218
I'll just conclude
with a few things.

00:28:46.218 --> 00:28:52.300
Look, when I started
my polling company,

00:28:52.300 --> 00:28:54.990
I built a computer and a
kit, programmed an assembler

00:28:54.990 --> 00:28:56.820
overnight, and had
overnight polling.

00:28:56.820 --> 00:29:02.440
So nobody is more enthusiastic
about technology than I was.

00:29:02.440 --> 00:29:05.260
And we are at the next
wave of personalization.

00:29:05.260 --> 00:29:07.990
Jobs are evolving in
the service sector.

00:29:07.990 --> 00:29:09.220
It's making luxury--

00:29:09.220 --> 00:29:12.900
I have a number of chapters
about how those things.

00:29:12.900 --> 00:29:16.600
Bill Gates once built
an enormous house

00:29:16.600 --> 00:29:17.850
as the world's richest person.

00:29:17.850 --> 00:29:22.870
And he had-- get this-- a
touch screen in every room.

00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:25.740
So luxury for less
is a big trend.

00:29:25.740 --> 00:29:29.400
Basic technology is
becoming almost universal.

00:29:29.400 --> 00:29:32.040
And life is driven by choices
that are more satisfying.

00:29:32.040 --> 00:29:35.340
And 10 years ago, that
would have been my list.

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:38.430
But today big tech is
becoming super powerful.

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:40.165
You have to acknowledge that.

00:29:40.165 --> 00:29:44.110
AI, without proper
rules of disclosure,

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:47.460
I think can be easily
abused, and could

00:29:47.460 --> 00:29:52.110
lead to some very traumatic
kinds of relationships,

00:29:52.110 --> 00:29:55.650
the likes of which we don't
even really understand.

00:29:55.650 --> 00:29:58.320
Big data does strip
people of privacy.

00:29:58.320 --> 00:29:59.400
Maybe they agree to it.

00:29:59.400 --> 00:30:00.510
Maybe not.

00:30:00.510 --> 00:30:03.170
Society is becoming
more balkanized.

00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:05.550
And something I didn't
go into in the talk

00:30:05.550 --> 00:30:09.120
is that actually as more and
more people have this 10 or 15

00:30:09.120 --> 00:30:12.840
years, and as more and more
people have successful careers,

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:15.240
the first thing they
get rid of is children.

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:18.750
Population growth in almost
all the developing countries

00:30:18.750 --> 00:30:23.460
is sinking.

00:30:23.460 --> 00:30:26.250
So policy changes?

00:30:26.250 --> 00:30:29.910
I recommend some changes
in antitrust laws,

00:30:29.910 --> 00:30:32.974
because they don't quite
fit emerging situations.

00:30:32.974 --> 00:30:34.890
We really have to be
better about the benefits

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:37.020
of the new economy
to every region.

00:30:37.020 --> 00:30:40.470
We have to be better about
disclosure of algorithms.

00:30:40.470 --> 00:30:42.870
And look, I worked with
a lot of engineers.

00:30:42.870 --> 00:30:47.070
And engineers just want to put
something really great and new

00:30:47.070 --> 00:30:48.030
into our society.

00:30:48.030 --> 00:30:53.160
But we don't often enough
study the implications

00:30:53.160 --> 00:30:54.540
that come out of that.

00:30:54.540 --> 00:30:57.480
We have to give people more
control over their data.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:31:00.060
We have to break the
cocooning somehow,

00:31:00.060 --> 00:31:02.790
forcing people to see new
choices that maybe they're

00:31:02.790 --> 00:31:04.350
closing out.

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:06.630
And I do a big thing
in the book about news,

00:31:06.630 --> 00:31:10.260
that I do think news
really needs that--

00:31:10.260 --> 00:31:13.650
the tech companies should
be in the platform business.

00:31:13.650 --> 00:31:15.930
But I worry when they
actually sort out

00:31:15.930 --> 00:31:17.250
the rankings of the stories.

00:31:17.250 --> 00:31:18.850
And crowdsourcing the truth?

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:21.540
Well, we'd still believe
that the Earth was flat

00:31:21.540 --> 00:31:23.790
if we went to a model like that.

00:31:23.790 --> 00:31:26.670
And I have a number of
things about making democracy

00:31:26.670 --> 00:31:29.580
more open and reducing
the size of that couch

00:31:29.580 --> 00:31:33.280
without requiring
everybody to vote.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:38.950
And I think, finally, I kind
of say that to take advantage,

00:31:38.950 --> 00:31:42.780
particularly for business
people, data is king.

00:31:42.780 --> 00:31:47.010
What I explain is, look,
if I have two companies,

00:31:47.010 --> 00:31:50.550
and one has a real data
set of its customers

00:31:50.550 --> 00:31:54.674
and the other doesn't,
well, on the one hand,

00:31:54.674 --> 00:31:57.090
the other company that doesn't
doesn't have all those data

00:31:57.090 --> 00:31:58.440
scientists costs and whatnot.

00:31:58.440 --> 00:32:02.190
But they have a higher
cost of marketing.

00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:05.850
The company that has a data set,
and understands its customers

00:32:05.850 --> 00:32:08.790
in the modern world can
market to their customers

00:32:08.790 --> 00:32:10.080
less expensively.

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:12.660
They have a fundamental
competitive advantage.

00:32:12.660 --> 00:32:14.940
They will drive the other
company out of business.

00:32:14.940 --> 00:32:17.790
It is just a matter of time.

00:32:17.790 --> 00:32:20.280
So for every business that
doesn't understand this,

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:22.590
they need a simple primer.

00:32:22.590 --> 00:32:26.490
Think services in today's
economy as much as products.

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:28.710
For every marketplace
and for every trend,

00:32:28.710 --> 00:32:30.330
there is a counter marketplace.

00:32:30.330 --> 00:32:31.980
There is a counter trend.

00:32:31.980 --> 00:32:34.260
You just have to think of it.

00:32:34.260 --> 00:32:37.369
And these everyday microtrends
create new opportunities.

00:32:37.369 --> 00:32:38.910
If you read the
book, you'll find out

00:32:38.910 --> 00:32:41.790
how women are the big
new purchasers of guns.

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:44.580
Whether it's beauty products
from Koreas or apartments

00:32:44.580 --> 00:32:46.180
that are set up for roommates.

00:32:46.180 --> 00:32:51.300
So I hope you enjoy the book,
in reading it, as much as I did,

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:54.600
find yourself in the book, or
find some interesting trends,

00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:56.850
or become a
microtrender yourself.

00:32:56.850 --> 00:32:57.969
Thank you very much.

00:32:57.969 --> 00:33:00.414
