00:33:03.874 --> 00:33:05.290
AUDIENCE: Given
all your expertise

00:33:05.290 --> 00:33:08.770
in polling, why specifically
were all the polls or a lot

00:33:08.770 --> 00:33:12.520
of the polls rather, so
wrong, so inaccurate?

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:14.935
What happened there?

00:33:14.935 --> 00:33:16.060
MARK PENN: A good question.

00:33:16.060 --> 00:33:17.320
I get that often.

00:33:17.320 --> 00:33:20.020
And let me say that I don't
actually think the polls,

00:33:20.020 --> 00:33:21.940
quote, unquote, were wrong.

00:33:21.940 --> 00:33:25.270
I think the level of
analysis of the polls

00:33:25.270 --> 00:33:29.350
was hugely unsophisticated.

00:33:29.350 --> 00:33:33.010
A poll is not something
that just anybody can read.

00:33:33.010 --> 00:33:36.220
Behind the poll is this
theory, a hypothesis,

00:33:36.220 --> 00:33:41.380
an understanding of elections,
voting groups, history.

00:33:41.380 --> 00:33:43.920
And when I did this polling,
say, with President Clinton,

00:33:43.920 --> 00:33:46.480
and I had to call it, I
had polls in 26 states

00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:48.850
up until the last day.

00:33:48.850 --> 00:33:53.230
I had a model of the probable
vote from each and every state.

00:33:53.230 --> 00:33:55.780
I had a model of the
electoral college.

00:33:55.780 --> 00:33:58.370
And I had national
polls on top of that.

00:33:58.370 --> 00:34:00.740
And all of these
things had to reconcile

00:34:00.740 --> 00:34:02.830
so that I had to tell
the president on the way

00:34:02.830 --> 00:34:07.013
back from South Dakota at 2:00
AM that I thought because Ralph

00:34:07.013 --> 00:34:09.429
Nader was going to get some
additional votes in California

00:34:09.429 --> 00:34:11.440
that he'd be below 50.

00:34:11.440 --> 00:34:14.110
And we hit it 49, 41 on the dot.

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:16.179
And there were polls
out there as much as 17

00:34:16.179 --> 00:34:18.100
who said it was 17.

00:34:18.100 --> 00:34:20.610
Now, you fast forward to today.

00:34:20.610 --> 00:34:23.540
The campaign cut
back on its polling.

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:25.540
They didn't see the
alternative universe.

00:34:25.540 --> 00:34:29.230
I always say that polling is
not about seeing those things

00:34:29.230 --> 00:34:30.850
that you already know.

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:32.239
You don't need polling for that.

00:34:32.239 --> 00:34:33.072
You already know it.

00:34:33.072 --> 00:34:35.530
It's about seeing those
things you don't know.

00:34:35.530 --> 00:34:38.770
So you're always spending
most of your time studying

00:34:38.770 --> 00:34:42.179
the 20% that is new
and unfamiliar to you,

00:34:42.179 --> 00:34:44.380
and I think they
stopped doing that.

00:34:44.380 --> 00:34:47.730
I think there were telltale
polls in Ohio and Iowa

00:34:47.730 --> 00:34:49.929
that were almost double digit.

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:52.330
And so you needed an
explanation for the fact

00:34:52.330 --> 00:34:54.610
that, wow, Donald
Trump was doing better

00:34:54.610 --> 00:34:58.690
in Republican states, but
getting killed by double digits

00:34:58.690 --> 00:35:01.150
in a bellwether of Ohio.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:02.740
And you had to
reconcile those facts.

00:35:02.740 --> 00:35:04.690
And nobody did.

00:35:04.690 --> 00:35:06.336
Cause they were both true.

00:35:06.336 --> 00:35:07.960
And that's exactly
what microtrends is.

00:35:07.960 --> 00:35:10.420
There was one trend
that he was doing better

00:35:10.420 --> 00:35:14.230
among Latinos that had
grown in numbers in turnout

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:15.310
in some of these states.

00:35:15.310 --> 00:35:17.300
Except the Cuban vote,
which turned out to be,

00:35:17.300 --> 00:35:20.080
again, another micro
trend that was missed.

00:35:20.080 --> 00:35:22.870
And then the old economy voters
going the other direction,

00:35:22.870 --> 00:35:26.530
balancing each other out,
creating polls that were close,

00:35:26.530 --> 00:35:29.710
and that were actually creating
an electoral college nightmare.

00:35:29.710 --> 00:35:32.800
Now, if I'd had
the resources, I'd

00:35:32.800 --> 00:35:35.260
like to think that I
would have picked that up.

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:37.210
But these campaigns
now had billions

00:35:37.210 --> 00:35:40.610
of dollars of resources,
and neither campaign--

00:35:40.610 --> 00:35:43.090
Look, with a campaign when
you're in the surprise upset,

00:35:43.090 --> 00:35:44.990
it's a surprise upset.

00:35:44.990 --> 00:35:48.880
So that comes together
actually in the last moment.

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:50.740
But you still see it rising.

00:35:50.740 --> 00:35:54.650
Because Donald Trump and Barack
Obama that I battled in 2008,

00:35:54.650 --> 00:35:55.840
they were a phenomenon.

00:35:55.840 --> 00:35:59.320
And phenomenons hockey stick up.

00:35:59.320 --> 00:36:01.050
If you don't stop
them here, trust me,

00:36:01.050 --> 00:36:03.220
you don't stop them here.

00:36:03.220 --> 00:36:07.110
So my basic point is, I
thought the analysis was

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:08.530
unsophisticated.

00:36:08.530 --> 00:36:12.010
And that analysis has to take
all of the various elements

00:36:12.010 --> 00:36:14.740
that you see,
reconcile all of them,

00:36:14.740 --> 00:36:16.630
and then come out with
intelligent judgment.

00:36:16.630 --> 00:36:18.610
And people got smarter.

00:36:18.610 --> 00:36:19.860
They got lazy.

00:36:19.860 --> 00:36:22.420
They got to believe that,
hey, anybody could do a poll,

00:36:22.420 --> 00:36:23.200
and read it.

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:25.192
And it's just not the case.

00:36:25.192 --> 00:36:25.900
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:36:25.900 --> 00:36:26.750
Appreciate it.

