I want a universally
easy, private voting

00:37:38.320 --> 00:37:40.400
system that can't be hacked.

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:43.570
So you've got to meet all
those criteria on the one hand.

00:37:43.570 --> 00:37:47.320
And then, on the other
hand, I don't want just

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:49.750
to encourage certain
groups to vote,

00:37:49.750 --> 00:37:51.580
because that really
is what creates

00:37:51.580 --> 00:37:53.350
these divisive campaigns.

00:37:53.350 --> 00:37:56.530
I want to be neutral in terms
of getting people off the couch.

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:59.620
And that means not just
registering people in cities.

00:37:59.620 --> 00:38:03.020
It means registering people
both in cities and rural areas,

00:38:03.020 --> 00:38:05.340
which is why I'd
register people at birth.

00:38:05.340 --> 00:38:07.900
There's no reason we shouldn't
have a national voter

00:38:07.900 --> 00:38:09.880
registry anymore.

00:38:09.880 --> 00:38:13.090
The government already
knows where to find you.

00:38:13.090 --> 00:38:14.980
I don't think that that
would be calamitous.

00:38:14.980 --> 00:38:18.640
And it would avoid a lot
of the legal problems

00:38:18.640 --> 00:38:20.336
with who can vote.

00:38:20.336 --> 00:38:23.120
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:23.120 --> 00:38:24.892
AUDIENCE: You alluded
to the Uber economy.

00:38:24.892 --> 00:38:26.350
And I know,
personally, my life has

00:38:26.350 --> 00:38:28.330
been changed by the
sharing economy, everything

00:38:28.330 --> 00:38:30.230
from how to get around,
to how to dress.

00:38:30.230 --> 00:38:32.630
Do you think it's a
trend or here to stay,

00:38:32.630 --> 00:38:33.837
the sharing economy?

00:38:33.837 --> 00:38:34.420
MARK PENN: No.

00:38:34.420 --> 00:38:36.550
Look, I think both
the sharing economy

00:38:36.550 --> 00:38:41.500
and, to me, the Uber economy
is about really understanding

00:38:41.500 --> 00:38:44.260
what your needs are, and
being able to deliver very

00:38:44.260 --> 00:38:48.860
precisely against those things.

00:38:48.860 --> 00:38:52.390
Look, even my son
has an app, which

00:38:52.390 --> 00:38:55.570
I disclose that
its my son, but he

00:38:55.570 --> 00:39:00.070
has an app called MTailor
that takes your measurements

00:39:00.070 --> 00:39:02.320
and then delivers
you custom clothes.

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:05.140
So in the past you
didn't have something

00:39:05.140 --> 00:39:08.980
that you could buy for $69
that was custom clothes.

00:39:08.980 --> 00:39:12.190
You could buy it for
$150, $250, $400.

00:39:12.190 --> 00:39:15.640
So what I really think is
the cost of personalization

00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:18.250
through technology, and
through the digital--

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:20.050
we always used to think
of digital layers.

00:39:20.050 --> 00:39:24.210
Every service, or every product
area, or piece of the economy

00:39:24.210 --> 00:39:26.260
will have a digital layer.

00:39:26.260 --> 00:39:29.830
And that digital layer
then has ramifications.

00:39:29.830 --> 00:39:31.870
Most of the time,
it makes the ability

00:39:31.870 --> 00:39:35.350
to really personalize and
customize things cheaper.

00:39:35.350 --> 00:39:39.490
And that is what enables you to
have it your way in virtually

00:39:39.490 --> 00:39:40.460
everything of life.

00:39:40.460 --> 00:39:42.580
And I think that is
the critical trend

00:39:42.580 --> 00:39:45.470
if I were opening a business
today that I'd want to meet.

00:39:45.470 --> 00:39:46.970
AUDIENCE: Do you
have an explanation

00:39:46.970 --> 00:39:50.450
for why people initially
want lots of choices,

00:39:50.450 --> 00:39:57.050
but then sort of coalesce
on fewer choices?

00:39:57.050 --> 00:40:00.562
MARK PENN: Well, see,
this is the thing.

00:40:00.562 --> 00:40:01.520
They want more choices.

00:40:01.520 --> 00:40:03.300
Because if I give
you just two choices,

00:40:03.300 --> 00:40:06.170
I like to say that the only
thing left in society with two

00:40:06.170 --> 00:40:08.570
choices is red or white wine.

00:40:08.570 --> 00:40:10.210
And you could have
rose, but rose

00:40:10.210 --> 00:40:11.646
is kind of like the Green Party.

00:40:11.646 --> 00:40:12.395
It's really small.

00:40:15.470 --> 00:40:19.990
And I think naturally then
what's evolved in this world,

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:22.180
I think naturally
people want more choice.

00:40:22.180 --> 00:40:25.380
They're just not happy
with limited choices.

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:27.350
But that's where the
paradox comes up,

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:29.990
which is if I make
you too happy,

00:40:29.990 --> 00:40:34.032
if I make you deliriously
happy, you will not, typically--

00:40:34.032 --> 00:40:35.240
that's not true of everybody.

00:40:35.240 --> 00:40:37.730
But let's say 70%,
80%, 90% of people

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:39.789
will just stick
within their choice.

00:40:39.789 --> 00:40:42.080
AUDIENCE: It's funny you
should say natural and evolve,

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:43.940
or evolution, or
whatever you said,

00:40:43.940 --> 00:40:47.060
because in evolutionary
theory that's

00:40:47.060 --> 00:40:50.720
exactly what happens, that you
have initially just one choice

00:40:50.720 --> 00:40:51.350
or lineage.

00:40:51.350 --> 00:40:53.840
And then it explodes
in all these forms.

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:56.680
And then it coalesces
on only a few.

00:40:56.680 --> 00:40:57.680
But then you have a few.

00:40:57.680 --> 00:41:01.370
And then these
become the one choice

00:41:01.370 --> 00:41:03.170
for those who went
that way, so to speak.

00:41:03.170 --> 00:41:03.920
It's very similar.

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:07.490
I'm just wondering if anybody
has sort of attempted to model

00:41:07.490 --> 00:41:09.530
human choices in the same way.

00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:10.700
MARK PENN: They have.

00:41:10.700 --> 00:41:12.200
I haven't done it.

00:41:12.200 --> 00:41:14.270
Somebody could take this
work and actually do

00:41:14.270 --> 00:41:17.690
a pretty interesting paper,
because I think you have a lot.

00:41:17.690 --> 00:41:19.590
Take the data and
information you have,

00:41:19.590 --> 00:41:25.820
and drive down to how either the
phenomenon that is so helpful

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:30.530
becomes so destructive in and of
itself in certain environments.

00:41:30.530 --> 00:41:32.210
Look, it may not matter.

00:41:32.210 --> 00:41:34.080
If you just order steak
or sushi every day,

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:35.900
who cares necessarily.

00:41:35.900 --> 00:41:38.944
Of course, it could be damaging
to your health or something.

00:41:38.944 --> 00:41:40.610
So there are a lot
of choices like this.

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:43.550
But I think the news
and political choices

00:41:43.550 --> 00:41:45.470
turn out to be
particularly divisive when

00:41:45.470 --> 00:41:46.715
you apply the theory there.

00:41:46.715 --> 00:41:48.590
AUDIENCE: You want to
get more people voting,

00:41:48.590 --> 00:41:51.110
but the question for me
then is, any technique

00:41:51.110 --> 00:41:54.510
you come up with seems to open
up the possibility of, well,

00:41:54.510 --> 00:41:57.630
one, people who are voting
based on the flipping of a coin,

00:41:57.630 --> 00:42:03.102
which is not necessarily
helpful, and, two, vote buying.

00:42:03.102 --> 00:42:05.060
Because anything that
makes things less private

00:42:05.060 --> 00:42:07.894
makes it easy to do vote buying
and other kinds of things.

00:42:07.894 --> 00:42:08.560
MARK PENN: Yeah.

00:42:08.560 --> 00:42:10.500
That's why I'm
concerned about that.

00:42:10.500 --> 00:42:12.820
I mean, look, we shouldn't
have voting on Tuesdays.

00:42:12.820 --> 00:42:14.210
They obviously should be--

00:42:14.210 --> 00:42:17.330
look, I think they
could be weekend long.

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:19.820
I think if we really wanted
to make it just easy-- if we

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:22.040
wanted to say,
let's update voting,

00:42:22.040 --> 00:42:25.040
or, let's say, if I gave
you guys here an exercise

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:27.530
and say, forget how we vote now.

00:42:27.530 --> 00:42:32.660
Design a system from the
ground up to maximize privacy,

00:42:32.660 --> 00:42:36.890
secret ballot, ease of choice,
and understanding of the ballot

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:39.740
and voting, you would design a
system that looks fundamentally

00:42:39.740 --> 00:42:41.240
different from today's.

00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:44.370
And I think that's the exercise
that we're failing to take.

00:42:44.370 --> 00:42:47.540
We don't care about
Tuesday voting.

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:49.460
There's no reason that
we keep anachronisms

00:42:49.460 --> 00:42:53.840
like that when we could, in
fact, design a new system,

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:55.900
and whether it's ATM
or something else.

00:42:55.900 --> 00:42:59.840
But I do believe we
do easy fixes now.

00:42:59.840 --> 00:43:02.330
And we're not really
starting from the ground up.

00:43:04.656 --> 00:43:06.030
AUDIENCE: So I
have a prediction.

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:08.640
And I was wondering
if you agreed.

00:43:08.640 --> 00:43:11.400
So a lot of the
trends you identified

00:43:11.400 --> 00:43:17.040
seem to be creating more
choice, seems to funnel people,

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:18.510
cocooning.

00:43:18.510 --> 00:43:22.680
It seems like that would lead to
less nationalism, less identity

00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:24.680
divided along country lines.

00:43:24.680 --> 00:43:28.440
And one example is more choice.

00:43:28.440 --> 00:43:30.410
In the '90s everyone
watched "Seinfeld."

00:43:30.410 --> 00:43:33.090
That was one thing
everyone could think.

00:43:33.090 --> 00:43:33.990
I'm an American.

00:43:33.990 --> 00:43:35.112
We all watch "Seinfeld."

00:43:35.112 --> 00:43:36.570
Before that there
were other shows.

00:43:36.570 --> 00:43:40.260
But now there's no hits like
on the scale of "Seinfeld"

00:43:40.260 --> 00:43:42.270
because there's so
much more choice.

00:43:42.270 --> 00:43:45.990
People are cocooning more and
know exactly what they want.

00:43:45.990 --> 00:43:48.240
Do you agree that
more choice will

00:43:48.240 --> 00:43:51.930
lead to less nationalism
and more of a global focus?

00:43:51.930 --> 00:43:55.170
Or maybe the identity lines will
divide along something other

00:43:55.170 --> 00:43:58.535
than American, Russian, Chinese?

00:43:58.535 --> 00:44:00.660
MARK PENN: Well, I talk
about your specific example

00:44:00.660 --> 00:44:04.710
in the book, which is I have
a section on intelligent TV.

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:07.440
And, in fact, I use
"Seinfeld" as the example.

00:44:07.440 --> 00:44:09.720
In the days of "Seinfeld"
and you were doing a TV

00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:13.290
show, to be successful
you would do jokes

00:44:13.290 --> 00:44:15.610
that 20% of the
country would laugh at,

00:44:15.610 --> 00:44:18.480
because your
audience was so huge.

00:44:18.480 --> 00:44:21.660
Now, when the cost of
making shows went down,

00:44:21.660 --> 00:44:25.540
and the number of channels went
up, there are now 400 shows.

00:44:25.540 --> 00:44:29.040
So now to be a hit
show I don't need 20%.

00:44:29.040 --> 00:44:30.000
2%.

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:31.530
I can be a microtrend show.

00:44:31.530 --> 00:44:34.230
So now we can have
intelligent shows.

00:44:34.230 --> 00:44:36.780
"Breaking Bad," "Homeland,"
et cetera, and we

00:44:36.780 --> 00:44:40.950
can have really horrible
shows, really gritty shows,

00:44:40.950 --> 00:44:43.950
which if you ever spend time
somewhere flipping the channels

00:44:43.950 --> 00:44:45.000
you can't even believe.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:48.870
So you have this enormously
expanded spectrum.

00:44:48.870 --> 00:44:52.800
So that means over in
Washington when you used to say,

00:44:52.800 --> 00:44:55.830
hey, are you watching TV, people
would all immediately say,

00:44:55.830 --> 00:44:58.500
no, I would never watch that TV.

00:44:58.500 --> 00:45:00.660
Now they actually
do because of that.

00:45:00.660 --> 00:45:05.130
So does that apply
in the spectrum?

00:45:05.130 --> 00:45:09.000
I don't know that that analogy
applies to whether or not

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:14.940
people will become more
nationalistic or patriotic.

00:45:14.940 --> 00:45:18.220
To me, I look at the trends
versus the counter trends.

00:45:18.220 --> 00:45:20.910
The more trends
suck one way, what's

00:45:20.910 --> 00:45:22.620
the counter trend to that?

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:27.510
So if there is a trend
towards reducing nationalism,

00:45:27.510 --> 00:45:29.910
being more
international in nature,

00:45:29.910 --> 00:45:32.970
did it spark a counter-trend
of being more national?

00:45:32.970 --> 00:45:34.650
It looks like it did.

00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:38.760
It looks like when
changes in values

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:41.920
become too fast or too
distant from a certain group--

00:45:41.920 --> 00:45:44.640
and remember, I didn't
go through it as much,

00:45:44.640 --> 00:45:51.330
but, in fact, the country
has never been older.

00:45:51.330 --> 00:45:53.850
And so the power has
shifted from younger voters

00:45:53.850 --> 00:45:55.840
to older voters.

00:45:55.840 --> 00:45:59.280
And so that power
shift also underscores

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:01.720
the cultural changes
that millennials see,

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:03.930
then create a reaction
in the older voters.

00:46:03.930 --> 00:46:07.770
So that's why I don't think it's
necessarily the case, because I

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:10.500
think the battle of trend
versus counter-trend

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:12.420
is more powerful than that.

00:46:12.420 --> 00:46:13.170
OK.

