So to be more specific,
I'm a vegetarian,

00:48:20.370 --> 00:48:23.760
and I see that there's clearly
this microtrend happening

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:27.160
of vegetarian and vegan options.

00:48:27.160 --> 00:48:29.730
But then when I leave
the city, for example,

00:48:29.730 --> 00:48:31.410
it's much harder to get those.

00:48:31.410 --> 00:48:32.670
So clearly it's a microtrend.

00:48:32.670 --> 00:48:34.590
It's on the rise, but
it's not everywhere.

00:48:34.590 --> 00:48:38.220
And whether it's that
example, like what

00:48:38.220 --> 00:48:40.500
are the obstacles that
you have to break down

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:43.200
to make a microtrend
into something huge?

00:48:43.200 --> 00:48:45.810
MARK PENN: Well, you
see, part of microtrends

00:48:45.810 --> 00:48:48.565
is you don't have to become big.

00:48:48.565 --> 00:48:53.320
The part of what's happened in
the economics of being able,

00:48:53.320 --> 00:48:55.860
whether it's TV, or Uber,
part of what's happened

00:48:55.860 --> 00:48:58.350
in the economics is it's OK.

00:48:58.350 --> 00:49:02.730
We can provide affordable
vegan food to you,

00:49:02.730 --> 00:49:06.240
and provide affordable sushi
for them, and steak for them,

00:49:06.240 --> 00:49:07.530
and chicken for them.

00:49:07.530 --> 00:49:09.930
And we didn't think we
could do that in the past.

00:49:09.930 --> 00:49:12.960
So the economics
enable microtrends

00:49:12.960 --> 00:49:16.380
to be successful at economic
curves that are much

00:49:16.380 --> 00:49:18.750
lower than we ever imagined.

